Call the flatMap operator on an observable that does not respect backpressure correctly:
1. flatMap calls {{request\(n)}} _once_
2. source observable calls onNext() n+1 times (this is illegal - should only call onNext() a maximum of n times)
3. the helper function addDemand sets 'demand' to MAX_VALUE, signalling the source observable to produce even more! 

{code}
       /**
         * Adds extra demand and protects against Longs rolling over
         *
         * @param extraDemand the amount of extra demand
         * @return the updated demand
         */
        private def addDemand(extraDemand: Long): Long = {
          this.synchronized {
            demand += extraDemand
            if (demand < 0) demand = Long.MaxValue
          }
          demand
        }
{code}

This happens when 'demand' is zero (the illegal n + 1th) call. As per the comments, this is supposed to protect from overflow, but under the above circumstances it in fact misbehaves.

At this point, it would be better if the operator threw an exception.
